The young aspirant is to learn the art of oratorical warfare on the field of battle itself : ul. . . pugnare in proelio deiceret (34. 8), where he will meet with foemen worthy of his steel (adversarii ferro non rudibus dimicantes, ib.). Just as the soldier must be furnished with every needful weapon, so must the orator possess a knowledge of every branch of culture: quere [oratorem] eron posse aleier exseiiere nec exstitisse unquam confirmo nisi eum qui tamquam in aciem omnibus armis instructus sie e'n sorum omne'bus orte'bus armatus exierit, 32. 9.
